02:00.000 --> 02:05.000
Process Management System

02:05.000 --> 02:08.000
So, let's move on to the very first point.

02:08.000 --> 02:10.000
This is a process management system.

02:10.000 --> 02:12.000
Where did it all come from?

02:12.000 --> 02:21.000
Surely, you all know that in the early 16th and even earlier centuries there was a simple craft production.

02:21.000 --> 02:25.000
The craftsman was engaged in all business processes on his own.

02:25.000 --> 02:28.000
He had no one, or at most there were a couple of assistants.

02:28.000 --> 02:30.000
There was nothing special.

02:30.000 --> 02:37.000
And he himself was engaged in both the purchase of materials and the manufacture of leather products, and so on.

02:37.000 --> 02:42.000
And he developed a strategy for his development, marketing, and so on.

02:42.000 --> 02:44.000
If, of course, he knew these words.

02:44.000 --> 02:46.000
Therefore, everyone was led by one person.

02:46.000 --> 02:50.000
We can say that all his crafts were a single business process.

02:50.000 --> 02:52.000
And he was the only owner.

02:52.000 --> 02:54.000
What happened over time?

02:54.000 --> 02:56.000
Over time, this happened.

02:56.000 --> 03:02.000
In 1776, Adam Smith developed the concept of functionality.

03:02.000 --> 03:07.000
That is, it means that now we have more than one person doing everything.

03:07.000 --> 03:11.000
And each of us is engaged in what he does best.

03:11.000 --> 03:13.000
It seems to be a completely logical concept.

03:13.000 --> 03:23.000
Indeed, why do you, specialists, well, let's say, in logistics, still engage in marketing, strategies, and the description of business processes?

03:23.000 --> 03:29.000
And IT, and translations, and phone calls, and coffee trays, and so on.

03:29.000 --> 03:31.000
Absolutely unnecessary.

03:31.000 --> 03:35.000
That is why Adam Smith proposed the concept of functional division.

03:35.000 --> 03:40.000
That is, from there, functional-oriented companies were born, which, unfortunately, are now the majority.

03:40.000 --> 03:49.000
This means that each specialist is engaged in his own narrow area of ​​activity, in which he, in which he has no equal.

03:50.000 --> 03:55.000
For example, there is a specialist like you, in logistics, or finance, or marketing.

03:55.000 --> 03:58.000
But this does not mean that you are engaged in all marketing.

03:58.000 --> 04:00.000
You are engaged in some small part of it.

04:00.000 --> 04:04.000
For example, in cooperation with large clients in the field of PR.

04:04.000 --> 04:09.000
Over time, this has taken on some ugly forms.

04:09.000 --> 04:13.000
Because there were too many narrow specialists.

04:13.000 --> 04:17.000
Everyone was engaged in a very, very narrow part of the activity.

04:17.000 --> 04:21.000
And as a result, no one was responsible for the whole business process.

04:21.000 --> 04:26.000
That is, as a result, the company began to turn into a group of small specialists,

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
each of whom did not know what his neighbor was doing in the room.

04:30.000 --> 04:37.000
And so, sooner or later, we had to come to the point that we partially returned to the times of craft production.

04:37.000 --> 04:39.000
What is it?

04:39.000 --> 04:44.000
We finally have these small, scattered pieces of functions, and unified processes began to take shape.

04:44.000 --> 04:50.000
But, unlike the very first time, when all production was considered as a single process,

04:50.000 --> 04:53.000
now we have processes that are different.

04:53.000 --> 04:57.000
On the main, on the business processes of management.

04:57.000 --> 05:01.000
And each of each process has its owner.

05:01.000 --> 05:04.000
Narrow specialists participate in the processes.

05:04.000 --> 05:07.000
Please, nothing changes here for health.

05:07.000 --> 05:09.000
The most important thing is that there is responsibility,

05:09.000 --> 05:11.000
and you can ask, what is wrong in the process?

05:11.000 --> 05:14.000
What is the result? What is the input? What is the output?

05:14.000 --> 05:16.000
What are the participants? Who is responsible for what?

05:16.000 --> 05:19.000
And finally, it becomes easier to manage the company.

05:19.000 --> 05:24.000
Probably because of this, the process management system now has more and more adherents,

05:24.000 --> 05:26.000
and many, many companies.

05:26.000 --> 05:32.000
And if before the process management system was the prerogative of only the most advanced Western companies,

05:32.000 --> 05:38.000
now the process management is implemented by small and medium companies of the Russian Federation.

05:39.000 --> 05:46.000
Let's consider the differences between the functional system and the process management system.

05:46.000 --> 05:53.000
If we take a factory for the production of some products,

05:53.000 --> 05:57.000
let's say, there are three workers working there.

05:57.000 --> 06:02.000
If we have a factory built according to the principle of functional division, what happens?

06:02.000 --> 06:06.000
The first worker only buys.

06:06.000 --> 06:08.000
He does not care what happens next.

06:08.000 --> 06:10.000
His task is to buy.

06:10.000 --> 06:14.000
He buys at the most attractive price,

06:14.000 --> 06:16.000
from the best suppliers, everything is great.

06:16.000 --> 06:18.000
He bought everything he needed.

06:18.000 --> 06:20.000
What to do next is not his problem.

06:20.000 --> 06:23.000
He does not care. He does not care at all.

06:23.000 --> 06:26.000
He did his job well, got a salary and went home happily.

06:26.000 --> 06:28.000
The second worker.

06:28.000 --> 06:32.000
The second worker gets this material and makes something out of it.

06:33.000 --> 06:37.000
The second worker does not care whether the consumer needs it or not.

06:37.000 --> 06:41.000
Maybe the consumer has completely different requirements for this product.

06:41.000 --> 06:43.000
He does not care either.

06:43.000 --> 06:48.000
His task is to get the material to the warehouse and then to transfer it to the sales manager.

06:48.000 --> 06:50.000
He is not interested in anything else.

06:50.000 --> 06:54.000
He did his job from A to B and then his function is over.

06:54.000 --> 06:56.000
The next worker.

06:56.000 --> 06:58.000
He took what was made and sells it.

06:58.000 --> 07:02.000
It is not important to tell the manufacturer that he needs a different product.

07:02.000 --> 07:04.000
The main thing is to sell it.

07:04.000 --> 07:06.000
What does it lead to?

07:06.000 --> 07:09.000
The organization is not inclined to make changes quickly,

07:09.000 --> 07:11.000
efficiently and smoothly.

07:11.000 --> 07:15.000
It reacts very slowly to changes in the environment

07:15.000 --> 07:18.000
and, in the end, it spends its competitive advantages.

07:18.000 --> 07:22.000
If this factory worked on the principle of a process control system,

07:22.000 --> 07:24.000
what would change?

07:24.000 --> 07:26.000
The first worker.

07:26.000 --> 07:30.000
He would be responsible for the purchase, production and sale of one product.

07:30.000 --> 07:32.000
Let's say, chairs.

07:32.000 --> 07:38.000
The second worker would be responsible for the purchase, production and sale of the third product.

07:38.000 --> 07:40.000
Let's say, refrigerators.

07:40.000 --> 07:43.000
The second product would be computers.

07:43.000 --> 07:46.000
The second or third worker would be responsible for this.

07:46.000 --> 07:51.000
Thus, each worker is fully responsible for the entire business process.

07:51.000 --> 07:56.000
The purchase, sale and production of one product.

07:56.000 --> 07:58.000
What does it lead to?

07:58.000 --> 08:00.000
The worker is aware of the consumer's requirements.

08:00.000 --> 08:02.000
He knows the needs of suppliers.

08:02.000 --> 08:04.000
He knows the features of the company's production.

08:04.000 --> 08:09.000
He can react quickly, efficiently and smoothly to changes in the environment.

08:09.000 --> 08:11.000
Suppliers may have changed something.

08:11.000 --> 08:14.000
They began to produce a more suitable material.

08:14.000 --> 08:17.000
Or the consumer may have new requirements for the product.

08:17.000 --> 08:21.000
This means that the consumer can quickly change the production process,

08:21.000 --> 08:24.000
purchase or sale of a product.

08:24.000 --> 08:26.000
The process changes quickly.

08:26.000 --> 08:30.000
Unlike the first case, when everyone is aware of the business process,

08:30.000 --> 08:33.000
although most of them do not know what the neighbor is doing.

08:33.000 --> 08:38.000
Let's consider the functional approach and the process approach.

08:38.000 --> 08:41.000
Let's compare what is good and what is bad.

08:41.000 --> 08:47.000
Based on what I just said, you may think that the functional approach is not suitable for anyone.

08:47.000 --> 08:49.000
It is a rudiment.

08:49.000 --> 08:51.000
It is not needed by anyone.

08:51.000 --> 08:53.000
It is wrong.

08:53.000 --> 08:56.000
Both approaches have their pros and cons.

08:56.000 --> 09:00.000
I want to note that the process approach is not suitable for all companies.

09:00.000 --> 09:03.000
Let's look at the pros and cons in more detail.

09:03.000 --> 09:07.000
If we talk about the functional approach, what are its pros?

09:07.000 --> 09:09.000
The pros are obvious.

09:09.000 --> 09:11.000
The first one is less expensive.

09:11.000 --> 09:17.000
Most likely, you know that a universal specialist who understands many issues

09:17.000 --> 09:21.000
is more expensive than a specialist who understands issues from A to B.

09:21.000 --> 09:24.000
But he understands this issue well.

09:24.000 --> 09:29.000
Therefore, if there are no such specialists in your company,

09:29.000 --> 09:38.000
the transition to the process approach means a sharp increase in the salary of such new universal specialists.

09:39.000 --> 09:42.000
As for the pros of the process approach,

09:42.000 --> 09:46.000
it is responsible for the overall result.

09:46.000 --> 09:51.000
If in the case of the first functional option,

09:51.000 --> 09:57.000
no one at this factory was responsible for what the factory produces,

09:57.000 --> 10:03.000
then in the second case, one manager who was responsible for the purchase, production and sale of a particular product,

10:03.000 --> 10:05.000
was responsible for the whole process.

10:05.000 --> 10:10.000
And we could be sure as the managers of such a factory that both the supplier and the consumer are satisfied.

10:10.000 --> 10:13.000
And if they are not satisfied, then the manager will fix everything.

10:13.000 --> 10:19.000
The pros are flexibility, speed, efficiency of decision-making.

10:19.000 --> 10:22.000
As for the cons, there is no place without them.

10:22.000 --> 10:25.000
Everything cannot be wonderful and chocolate.

10:25.000 --> 10:27.000
The functional approach.

10:27.000 --> 10:29.000
What are the cons?

10:29.000 --> 10:33.000
The cons are opposite to the pros of the process approach.

10:33.000 --> 10:38.000
If the process approach is flexible, then the functional approach is not flexible.

10:38.000 --> 10:44.000
This is the lack of speed in decision-making on the change of the process.

10:44.000 --> 10:49.000
This is the lack of responsibility for the overall result of the process.

10:49.000 --> 10:54.000
This is the lack of efficiency of the whole process.

10:54.000 --> 10:57.000
Yes, your divisions can work perfectly.

10:57.000 --> 10:59.000
The buyer buys everything quickly.

10:59.000 --> 11:02.000
The manufacturer produces everything very quickly.

11:02.000 --> 11:08.000
The seller sells everything quickly and you don't have anything in the warehouse for a long time.

11:08.000 --> 11:13.000
But for some reason your suppliers are not optimal over time,

11:13.000 --> 11:16.000
with higher prices than on the market.

11:16.000 --> 11:19.000
And your customers refuse you for some reason,

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
because you need to sell differently.

11:22.000 --> 11:24.000
Further.

11:24.000 --> 11:30.000
The functional approach cannot be without problems at the junction between divisions.

11:30.000 --> 11:34.000
If you have a lot of specialists involved in the process,

11:34.000 --> 11:37.000
who understand their narrow problems,

11:37.000 --> 11:40.000
then the transition from one specialist to another,

11:40.000 --> 11:44.000
each work in the business process leads to problems.

11:44.000 --> 11:47.000
One transition is one problem, another transition is another problem,

11:47.000 --> 11:48.000
more and more.

11:48.000 --> 11:50.000
The more specialists in your network,

11:50.000 --> 11:52.000
who are involved in your business process,

11:52.000 --> 11:54.000
the more problems there will be.

11:54.000 --> 11:57.000
And be sure that it will be very difficult to change such a process.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.000
It is easier to do it from scratch.

11:59.000 --> 12:05.000
And finally, this leads to conflicts between divisions,

12:05.000 --> 12:08.000
or between specialists, people, groups, and so on.

12:08.000 --> 12:11.000
The disadvantages of the process approach.

12:11.000 --> 12:12.000
He also has disadvantages.

12:12.000 --> 12:13.000
He is not perfect.

12:13.000 --> 12:15.000
First, he is more expensive.

12:15.000 --> 12:17.000
And there is duplication of work.

12:17.000 --> 12:19.000
Let's go back to the example of the factory.

12:19.000 --> 12:22.000
In the first case, one manager was engaged in the purchase.

12:22.000 --> 12:28.000
In the second case, the manager was engaged in the purchase and production of sales.

12:28.000 --> 12:30.000
The second manager was engaged in the purchase and production of sales.

12:30.000 --> 12:33.000
The third manager was engaged in the purchase and production of sales.

12:33.000 --> 12:34.000
And so on.

12:34.000 --> 12:36.000
In fact, the purchase was done by three people.

12:36.000 --> 12:38.000
This is duplication.

12:38.000 --> 12:39.000
This is a complication.

12:39.000 --> 12:42.000
But let's remember the advantages.

12:42.000 --> 12:43.000
It is the responsibility for the result.

12:43.000 --> 12:45.000
It is a better product.

12:45.000 --> 12:47.000
Further.

12:47.000 --> 12:53.000
Let's say that we have a few such managers in our company.

12:53.000 --> 12:58.000
And we need a person in each of the processes who will help.

12:58.000 --> 13:01.000
From the point of view of marketing, for example.

13:01.000 --> 13:03.000
But such a specialist is the only one.

13:03.000 --> 13:05.000
How to break him between three processes?

13:05.000 --> 13:07.000
Let's say that we have three managers.

13:07.000 --> 13:10.000
Responsible for the chair, for the computer, and for something else.

13:10.000 --> 13:12.000
But we have only one marketing specialist.

13:12.000 --> 13:14.000
Which business process should you include?

13:14.000 --> 13:15.000
This is unknown.

13:15.000 --> 13:16.000
This is a conflict of resources.

13:16.000 --> 13:17.000
This is not clear.

13:17.000 --> 13:19.000
This is also a minus of the process approach.

13:19.000 --> 13:25.000
Especially if you have very few narrowly specialized workers.

13:25.000 --> 13:30.000
Accordingly, if we have few specialists in our company, who understand everything.

13:30.000 --> 13:32.000
Then we have a conflict of resources.

13:32.000 --> 13:36.000
And we can not equally divide them into different business processes.

13:36.000 --> 13:42.000
You have to sit with the same specialist in this process, and in this, and in this, and in this.

13:42.000 --> 13:43.000
That is, a conflict of resources.

13:43.000 --> 13:48.000
And the third drawback of the process approach is that we have high requirements for specialists.

13:48.000 --> 13:51.000
In a company where a process approach is implemented,

13:51.000 --> 13:57.000
one person can not sit alone to hand over a piece of paper from department A to department B.

13:57.000 --> 13:58.000
That's it.

13:58.000 --> 14:02.000
This means that the specialist must perform the maximum functions.

14:02.000 --> 14:06.000
Otherwise, why do you need such a narrowly specialized person in the company?

14:06.000 --> 14:09.000
Not in all organizations this is possible.

14:09.000 --> 14:17.000
Therefore, if in your company you have a lot of specialists, who do some very small, small, small work.

14:17.000 --> 14:22.000
This means that the process approach is temporary for you.

14:22.000 --> 14:31.000
Until there are more, more universal specialists, who understand a large number of functions and work.

14:31.000 --> 14:38.000
Now we have come to the most important point, which in our course will probably be without it.

14:38.000 --> 14:40.000
It makes no sense to continue.

14:40.000 --> 14:43.000
This is the difference between a business process and a function.

14:43.000 --> 14:46.000
Now we talked about the process approach and the functional approach.

14:46.000 --> 14:51.000
I think you already roughly understand the difference between a process and a function.

14:51.000 --> 14:58.000
If you formulated the definition of a business process in your own way, how do you think, how would you formulate it?

14:58.000 --> 15:04.000
Well, probably you would say that this is a connection of several works or functions,

15:04.000 --> 15:10.000
which are designed to transform something at the input into something that will be at the output.

15:10.000 --> 15:14.000
Otherwise, any process happens.

15:14.000 --> 15:16.000
A business process is not an exception.

15:16.000 --> 15:21.000
And it is very important here that there is something at the input and something at the output.

15:21.000 --> 15:25.000
And to the fact that at the output and to the fact that at the input certain requirements are presented.

15:25.000 --> 15:30.000
If the process has no result, then it is not a business process, it is not clear what.

15:31.000 --> 15:35.000
If we talk about a function, then it is a component of a business process.

15:35.000 --> 15:40.000
This is a certain work, repetitive, which can be included in several business processes.

15:40.000 --> 15:44.000
But the main thing is just a repetitive periodic action.

15:44.000 --> 15:50.000
There is no emphasis on the fact that it is designed to transform something at the input into something at the output.

15:50.000 --> 15:54.000
That is why if we compare a business process and a function,

15:54.000 --> 15:58.000
then we can give the following characteristics to a function and a business process.

15:58.000 --> 16:02.000
Let's start with a function as a component of a business process.

16:02.000 --> 16:06.000
A function is a set of homogeneous activities.

16:06.000 --> 16:10.000
Homogeneous means that they are identical, similar.

16:10.000 --> 16:13.000
For example, a purchase.

16:13.000 --> 16:15.000
In general, this is a function.

16:15.000 --> 16:21.000
Next, this is a set of narrowly specialized activities.

16:21.000 --> 16:25.000
For example, PR, cooperation with the media.

16:26.000 --> 16:30.000
These are all functions that are included in a business process marketing.

16:30.000 --> 16:33.000
And then, the most important, I emphasize again,

16:33.000 --> 16:36.000
that a function is a component of a business process.

16:36.000 --> 16:39.000
A brick from which a whole wall is made.

16:39.000 --> 16:43.000
If we move on to a business process, then it is a set of various types of activities.

16:43.000 --> 16:46.000
We remember that in the example of a factory we talked about a business process,

16:46.000 --> 16:49.000
which is called from purchase to sale.

16:49.000 --> 16:54.000
That is, there are functions of purchase, sale and production.

16:54.000 --> 16:57.000
If we talk about a business process,

16:57.000 --> 17:02.000
we also take into account that business processes are interconnected.

17:02.000 --> 17:08.000
That is, they are not separate functions that exist in nature and in your company.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.000
They are connected to each other.

17:10.000 --> 17:14.000
The entrance of one business process is the exit of another business process, and so on.

17:14.000 --> 17:17.000
If the process is not connected to anything, it is not needed.

17:17.000 --> 17:21.000
Or this is a sign of inoptimism, it needs to be tied to something.

17:22.000 --> 17:25.000
This is the presence of entrances and exits.

17:25.000 --> 17:29.000
A business process is another important feature of it.

17:29.000 --> 17:33.000
We remember that a business process is designed to transform something into something.

17:33.000 --> 17:37.000
If the transformation does not take place, then it is not a business process.

17:37.000 --> 17:39.000
Next, the presence of results.

17:39.000 --> 17:42.000
And if there is no result, and this is some kind of partiality,

17:42.000 --> 17:46.000
or it is not clear what, then this is an improvement.

17:46.000 --> 17:50.000
A business process is either wrongly allocated, or it functions incorrectly.

17:50.000 --> 17:52.000
That is, something needs to be done with it.

17:52.000 --> 17:55.000
And most importantly, it consists of functions.

17:55.000 --> 17:58.000
Thus, we have compared a function and a business process.

17:58.000 --> 18:01.000
And now, when we talk about a business process,

18:01.000 --> 18:07.000
we mean the whole function, which is designed to transform an input into a result.

18:07.000 --> 18:09.000
And now the most interesting thing.

18:09.000 --> 18:13.000
How does the process management system in an organization work?

18:13.000 --> 18:16.000
What do you think it starts with?

18:16.000 --> 18:19.000
For example, someone will tell you that you need to describe a process,

18:19.000 --> 18:21.000
or you need to allocate processes,

18:21.000 --> 18:26.000
or you need to quickly follow the structure of the company and start allocating something from it.

18:26.000 --> 18:30.000
I do not want to upset you, but both answers will be wrong.

18:30.000 --> 18:34.000
Because you need to start with the most important thing, with the strategy of the company's development.

18:34.000 --> 18:39.000
Without understanding where your company is going, you will not be able to allocate business processes,

18:39.000 --> 18:44.000
because you will not be able to understand which business directions are key to your activities.

18:44.000 --> 18:48.000
And this means that you will not be able to allocate processes to the main and providing ones.

18:48.000 --> 18:51.000
If you do not know the strategy of the company's development,

18:51.000 --> 18:53.000
you will not be able to analyze business processes,

18:53.000 --> 18:55.000
which are important, which are less important,

18:55.000 --> 18:59.000
which are problematic, which are less problematic, and so on.

18:59.000 --> 19:02.000
If you do not know the strategy of your company,

19:02.000 --> 19:05.000
you will not know the needs of your clients,

19:05.000 --> 19:10.000
and you will not be able to form the right requirements for the result of all your business processes.

19:10.000 --> 19:14.000
Without the strategy, it is not possible to implement the process management system.

19:14.000 --> 19:18.000
The strategy is not a piece of paper that is taken from the company,

19:18.000 --> 19:20.000
and then it is not shown to anyone,

19:20.000 --> 19:23.000
and it is put on the shelves along with the regulations.

19:23.000 --> 19:27.000
The strategy is a real concept that everyone in the organization knows.

19:27.000 --> 19:30.000
One way or another, but they should know it.

19:30.000 --> 19:35.000
When there is a strategy, we can safely move on to allocating business processes.

19:36.000 --> 19:39.000
The first point is that we have developed a strategy of the company

19:39.000 --> 19:42.000
and brought it to each unit, to each employee.

19:42.000 --> 19:45.000
The balance score card is used for this,

19:45.000 --> 19:47.000
that is, the BSC system.

19:47.000 --> 19:50.000
I think you will be told about it in another course.

19:50.000 --> 19:53.000
Next, when we already have a strategy,

19:53.000 --> 19:55.000
we allocate business processes to the company,

19:55.000 --> 19:59.000
then we describe them, go further, look at the processes,

19:59.000 --> 20:02.000
and describe it all again to each employee.

20:02.000 --> 20:04.000
Now, when we have described it all,

20:04.000 --> 20:08.000
we analyze it all according to the strategy that we have developed before.

20:08.000 --> 20:13.000
And then, when we have described it all, analyzed it, optimized it,

20:13.000 --> 20:16.000
we have regulated the processes that have already been optimized,

20:16.000 --> 20:21.000
and after that, we will have specific positions in the organization.

20:21.000 --> 20:24.000
After everything is optimized,

20:24.000 --> 20:27.000
we will be able to develop our ideal organization.

20:27.000 --> 20:32.000
In most companies, the organization is created almost from the beginning,

20:32.000 --> 20:36.000
without understanding the basic and providing business processes.

20:36.000 --> 20:38.000
Therefore, it is often not optimal,

20:38.000 --> 20:40.000
it does not collide with the processes.

20:40.000 --> 20:42.000
In the process management system, the process is the primary,

20:42.000 --> 20:44.000
and not the structure.

20:44.000 --> 20:47.000
In the functional approach, everything is vice versa.

20:47.000 --> 20:51.000
The structure is more important, and the processes are not so important.

20:51.000 --> 20:56.000
Let's consider, for example, some companies,

20:56.000 --> 20:58.000
let's call them Evrica,

20:58.000 --> 21:03.000
how the organizational structure of the company can look like,

21:03.000 --> 21:05.000
where the process approach is implemented,

21:05.000 --> 21:07.000
and where the functional approach is implemented.

21:07.000 --> 21:10.000
Let's say we have a company,

21:10.000 --> 21:13.000
it is engaged in the purchase of tea, clothes, and furniture.

21:13.000 --> 21:15.000
Well, an absurd example, but nevertheless.

21:15.000 --> 21:18.000
If we implement a functional approach there,

21:18.000 --> 21:21.000
we will have a department of purchase,

21:21.000 --> 21:24.000
a department of storage, and a department of sale.

21:24.000 --> 21:28.000
It does not matter that it deals with three absolutely incompatible types of activities,

21:28.000 --> 21:30.000
tea, clothes, and furniture.

21:30.000 --> 21:32.000
It does not matter at all, there will be three departments.

21:32.000 --> 21:35.000
If the process approach was implemented in this company,

21:35.000 --> 21:38.000
its organizational structure would be completely different.

21:38.000 --> 21:41.000
There would be a department of tea, clothes, and furniture.

21:41.000 --> 21:45.000
Thus, we understand that in the second case,

21:45.000 --> 21:48.000
in the department of tea, there would be departments of purchase,

21:48.000 --> 21:52.000
tea, storage, tea, and sale of tea.

21:52.000 --> 21:55.000
The same would apply to furniture and clothes.

21:55.000 --> 21:59.000
In the case of a functional approach in the company,

21:59.000 --> 22:01.000
in the department of purchases,

22:01.000 --> 22:05.000
there would be managers of tea, clothes, and furniture.

22:05.000 --> 22:08.000
Storage, sales, everything is the same.

22:08.000 --> 22:13.000
I want to say right away that I have never seen a company

22:13.000 --> 22:16.000
where the process approach was implemented to such an extent.

22:16.000 --> 22:18.000
In principle, this is not always necessary,

22:18.000 --> 22:20.000
because the creative organizational structure,

22:20.000 --> 22:24.000
which has existed for many years and is not always absolutely harmful,

22:24.000 --> 22:26.000
does not make sense.

22:26.000 --> 22:29.000
You can make an intermediate compromise option,

22:29.000 --> 22:31.000
which is called the matrix.

22:31.000 --> 22:35.000
Let's say, in the case of the same company,

22:35.000 --> 22:38.000
the matrix option would look like this,

22:38.000 --> 22:43.000
that it would have at the same time a department of purchases, storage, and sales,

22:43.000 --> 22:49.000
but there would also be a manager of tea, furniture, and clothes.

22:50.000 --> 22:56.000
In principle, this would allow each manager to examine the entire business process

22:56.000 --> 23:03.000
and to see its problems, inputs, outputs, results, satisfaction of customers,

23:03.000 --> 23:06.000
interaction with suppliers, and so on, to observe all participants.

23:06.000 --> 23:11.000
But this would lead to a very serious minus.

23:11.000 --> 23:16.000
This main minus is that all participants in the business process

23:16.000 --> 23:23.000
of tea, furniture, and clothes would be two bosses.

23:23.000 --> 23:26.000
The first is the head of the department of purchases,

23:26.000 --> 23:28.000
and the second is the project manager.

23:28.000 --> 23:31.000
If their wishes were conflicted,

23:31.000 --> 23:34.000
then the performer would not know whom to submit to.

23:34.000 --> 23:38.000
The principle of double submission is the main minus of such a compromise option.

23:38.000 --> 23:41.000
Therefore, if you do not have a compromise option,

23:41.000 --> 23:43.000
then you will have to decide what the structure will be,

23:43.000 --> 23:45.000
whether it will be a process or a matrix one,

23:45.000 --> 23:48.000
or maybe you will choose a functional one.

23:48.000 --> 23:52.000
So, we have already talked a lot about business processes,

23:52.000 --> 23:54.000
that everything is great,

23:54.000 --> 23:56.000
but do business processes really exist?

23:56.000 --> 23:58.000
Our clients often ask us questions.

23:58.000 --> 24:00.000
You have described all these business processes,

24:00.000 --> 24:02.000
but it seems to us that they do not exist.

24:02.000 --> 24:06.000
They exist, but in fact, they are very fragmented.

24:06.000 --> 24:10.000
As I said, the fact is that in most companies there is a functional approach,

24:11.000 --> 24:15.000
so it is very difficult to collect a bunch of small functions,

24:15.000 --> 24:17.000
narrow-specialized functions,

24:17.000 --> 24:19.000
and it is also very difficult to see it as a whole.

24:19.000 --> 24:24.000
Secondly, they are not formalized and not described.

24:24.000 --> 24:26.000
In fact, in most companies we worked with,

24:26.000 --> 24:28.000
how is the business process described?

24:28.000 --> 24:30.000
It's an amazing spectacle.

24:30.000 --> 24:34.000
Separately, there is some instruction from some manager for some reason,

24:34.000 --> 24:37.000
separately, there is an instruction from some department,

24:37.000 --> 24:39.000
separately, there is a position of the departments.

24:39.000 --> 24:41.000
They do not clash with each other in principle,

24:41.000 --> 24:43.000
or they are absolute copies,

24:43.000 --> 24:45.000
only the cap is different.

24:45.000 --> 24:47.000
This is not a description of business processes,

24:47.000 --> 24:51.000
it is just a list of functions that came to the head of the person who wrote it,

24:51.000 --> 24:55.000
when he was given this task, and he was told that this task should have been done yesterday.

24:55.000 --> 24:56.000
Next.

24:56.000 --> 24:58.000
Business processes exist.

24:58.000 --> 25:00.000
They cannot be not exist,

25:00.000 --> 25:04.000
because otherwise the company would have collapsed.

25:04.000 --> 25:06.000
But in most companies,

25:06.000 --> 25:08.000
even taking into account the fact that they exist,

25:08.000 --> 25:10.000
no one is responsible for the result.

25:10.000 --> 25:14.000
Or it happens only in a number of business processes, not in all.

25:14.000 --> 25:16.000
Therefore, if no one is responsible for the result,

25:16.000 --> 25:18.000
no one sees the situation as a whole,

25:18.000 --> 25:20.000
again, the business process is not visible to anyone at all,

25:20.000 --> 25:24.000
and it can be considered that it does not exist.

25:24.000 --> 25:25.000
Next.

25:25.000 --> 25:30.000
Very often business processes are very fragmented.

25:30.000 --> 25:34.000
That is, many specialists participate in this business process,

25:34.000 --> 25:37.000
no one knows what it is all about.

25:37.000 --> 25:41.000
Therefore, they can be considered to be part of something,

25:41.000 --> 25:42.000
of one big company,

25:42.000 --> 25:45.000
but it is not clear what their activity leads to.

25:46.000 --> 25:51.000
Very often there is additional control in organizations for each transfer.

25:51.000 --> 25:55.000
That is, if one manager transfers the result of his work to another manager,

25:55.000 --> 25:57.000
then to the third, fourth, fifth,

25:57.000 --> 26:00.000
there is a conflict at every crossroads,

26:00.000 --> 26:03.000
there is a check, a checkpoint,

26:03.000 --> 26:10.000
and this control leads to the fact that all the connection with what should be at the output is lost.

26:10.000 --> 26:13.000
It is not clear at all, but everything is controlled.

26:14.000 --> 26:18.000
And most importantly, very often there is no relevant IT support

26:18.000 --> 26:21.000
to describe and optimize business processes.

26:21.000 --> 26:25.000
Believe me, describing business processes in RDA is not the most wonderful thing.

26:26.000 --> 26:32.000
So, if you, as a manager of an organization,

26:32.000 --> 26:38.000
decided that your organization should have a process management system,

26:38.000 --> 26:42.000
how to build it step by step?

26:42.000 --> 26:43.000
Step number one.

26:43.000 --> 26:45.000
Select business processes.

26:45.000 --> 26:47.000
Until we talk about their description,

26:47.000 --> 26:49.000
until we just select them.

26:49.000 --> 26:53.000
That is, the main business processes that provide business management processes.

26:53.000 --> 26:54.000
Great.

26:54.000 --> 26:56.000
There should be about 20 of them, no more.

26:57.000 --> 26:58.000
Next.

26:58.000 --> 26:59.000
We describe them.

26:59.000 --> 27:01.000
We describe only the boundaries,

27:01.000 --> 27:03.000
that is, at the input and at the output.

27:03.000 --> 27:05.000
In order to make sure that we have selected them correctly,

27:05.000 --> 27:08.000
each business process has its own clear and definite result.

27:08.000 --> 27:11.000
Maybe at this stage we will correct the selection.

27:11.000 --> 27:12.000
Next.

27:12.000 --> 27:13.000
We describe them.

27:14.000 --> 27:17.000
Namely, the composition of the functions that each of them includes.

27:17.000 --> 27:21.000
And we describe the executors for each and every function.

27:21.000 --> 27:22.000
Next.

27:22.000 --> 27:24.000
When we have described all of this,

27:24.000 --> 27:26.000
we assign the owners for each business process.

27:26.000 --> 27:29.000
For the first process, for the second, for the third, for the fourth, for the fifth.

27:30.000 --> 27:32.000
And when we have highlighted all of this,

27:32.000 --> 27:36.000
finally, we can regulate this business process,

27:36.000 --> 27:39.000
create a system of accounting for the business process,

27:39.000 --> 27:42.000
and put it all on the owners of this business process,

27:42.000 --> 27:44.000
who will observe this system

27:44.000 --> 27:50.000
and regularly report to their boss about how things are going in their business process.

27:51.000 --> 27:56.000
Usually, there are many business process reports.

27:56.000 --> 27:58.000
They are different in each organization.

27:58.000 --> 28:04.000
In principle, there is a plan-fact report on indicators for each project, that is, KPI.

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
It can be a card of some contract,

28:07.000 --> 28:10.000
if we take the business process at the lowest level.

28:10.000 --> 28:13.000
In principle, the accounting system can be any.

28:13.000 --> 28:16.000
It can be in Wardia, it can be in Excel,

28:16.000 --> 28:19.000
it can be in your corporate information system.

28:19.000 --> 28:21.000
The main thing is that it is there,

28:21.000 --> 28:24.000
otherwise no one will need the business process description.

28:24.000 --> 28:27.000
And all this accounting system for business processes

28:27.000 --> 28:32.000
must be combined with your operating accounting system and management accounting system.

28:32.000 --> 28:37.000
That is, all these accounting systems must be bound together.

28:37.000 --> 28:40.000
Otherwise, you have one accounting system for processes,

28:40.000 --> 28:43.000
management accounting is another, financial accounting is something else,

28:43.000 --> 28:45.000
operational accounting is generally something else,

28:45.000 --> 28:48.000
strategic accounting is nothing at all.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
Everything should be a single accounting system.

28:51.000 --> 29:01.000
Accordingly, what can you implement the business process management system in your company for?

29:01.000 --> 29:06.000
The answer to this question you must ask yourself, your management,

29:06.000 --> 29:11.000
before you dive into the process approach of your company.

29:11.000 --> 29:15.000
Because, as with absolutely any innovation, you need to set a goal.

29:15.000 --> 29:16.000
Why are you doing this?

29:16.000 --> 29:22.000
The answer like, it's fashionable, everyone does it, I think it will help us, is not accepted.

29:22.000 --> 29:24.000
It should be a real, justified answer.

29:24.000 --> 29:29.000
For example, you need to increase the controllability and transparency of your company, of your business.

29:29.000 --> 29:33.000
Or you need to optimize business processes, you have too high costs.

29:33.000 --> 29:36.000
Or you need to build an effective infrastructure,

29:36.000 --> 29:38.000
because you have a high flow of personnel,

29:38.000 --> 29:41.000
changes are happening very slowly, it is not clear what is happening.

29:41.000 --> 29:46.000
Or you have some new business direction,

29:46.000 --> 29:49.000
you need to understand how it will deal with the already existing,

29:49.000 --> 29:52.000
what processes will change and how to implement it correctly.

29:52.000 --> 29:56.000
Or you want to publish business, for example, to introduce a franchise.

29:56.000 --> 30:00.000
Or you want to introduce an automated accounting system.

30:00.000 --> 30:06.000
Or you want to conduct, for example, audit of personnel and select completely new frames,

30:06.000 --> 30:08.000
because the current ones will not suit you.

30:08.000 --> 30:12.000
Or it is a financial accounting, or it is a merger and absorption,

30:12.000 --> 30:15.000
it can be an increase in market value, in general, it can be anything.

30:15.000 --> 30:18.000
But the main thing is that the goal is clearly described and understood by everyone.

30:18.000 --> 30:22.000
Because without a goal, it is not clear why you are doing this.

30:22.000 --> 30:27.000
Without a goal, you will not be motivated to implement this system,

30:27.000 --> 30:30.000
so that it is not from under the stick.

30:30.000 --> 30:36.000
If your boss told you that we are introducing a process system,

30:36.000 --> 30:40.000
do not be afraid, come to him, ask why, let him tell you,

30:40.000 --> 30:44.000
let him hold a single seminar on business processes of your company.

30:44.000 --> 30:49.000
For example, in a company where I once worked as an internal business analyst,

30:49.000 --> 30:55.000
its director, the owner, decided that we would introduce a process management system.

30:55.000 --> 30:57.000
What did it lead to?

30:57.000 --> 31:00.000
I came, I was told that everyone was already aware,

31:00.000 --> 31:04.000
everyone would participate in the description of business processes and their optimization.

31:04.000 --> 31:08.000
I believed, and began to go, respectively, to people, to ask.

31:08.000 --> 31:12.000
Are business processes high-level? We'll talk about it a little later.

31:12.000 --> 31:16.000
Or are business processes of lower level?

31:16.000 --> 31:18.000
Described in what environment? And so on and so forth.

31:18.000 --> 31:21.000
But no one could answer all my questions, because they did not understand what it was about.

31:21.000 --> 31:24.000
As a result, it turned out that someone had heard about it.

31:24.000 --> 31:29.000
But in fact, no one could imagine what it was, why it was necessary.

31:29.000 --> 31:34.000
As a result, we held a general seminar for the heads of departments,

31:34.000 --> 31:37.000
where it was told what a process management system is,

31:37.000 --> 31:40.000
why it is introduced in a company, what are its pros and cons,

31:40.000 --> 31:43.000
what will be introduced in this particular company, where we will work,

31:43.000 --> 31:46.000
how it will happen, who is responsible, and so on.

31:46.000 --> 31:48.000
After this seminar, everything was very clear.

31:48.000 --> 31:53.000
And after this seminar, managers immediately began to come to us in the business processes department

31:53.000 --> 31:56.000
and say, I want to participate, I would like to optimize this process,

31:56.000 --> 31:58.000
I have such and such wishes for it.

31:58.000 --> 32:02.000
Without such an introductory seminar, everyone was tuned to some one wave.

32:02.000 --> 32:05.000
It is impossible to introduce a process management system.

32:07.000 --> 32:12.000
So, how does the system function?

32:12.000 --> 32:16.000
First, we develop a process model of your company as it is.

32:16.000 --> 32:17.000
This is very important.

32:17.000 --> 32:23.000
That is, you do not need to immediately describe and generate options on the topic of how you want it to work.

32:23.000 --> 32:25.000
First, we describe the situation as it is.

32:25.000 --> 32:28.000
Without having an idea of ​​what we have today,

32:28.000 --> 32:33.000
we will not be able to understand all the cons, all the interactions,

32:33.000 --> 32:39.000
and we will not be able to analyze and develop a high-quality system of process management of the organization.

32:39.000 --> 32:41.000
So, first, the model as it is.

32:41.000 --> 32:43.000
Then, the analysis of the model as it is.

32:43.000 --> 32:45.000
Then, the development of the model as it should be.

32:45.000 --> 32:47.000
Then, the development of the regulations as it should be.

32:47.000 --> 32:49.000
And only then, the optimization of the organizational structure.

32:49.000 --> 32:51.000
Only in such a sequence.

32:53.000 --> 32:55.000
So, what's next?

32:57.000 --> 33:05.000
If we talk about how we analyze business processes as it is,

33:05.000 --> 33:07.000
analyze our model as it is,

33:07.000 --> 33:11.000
then we must refer to the following tools.

33:11.000 --> 33:15.000
We look at the strategy document of your organization.

33:15.000 --> 33:17.000
We look at the strategic maps of your company.

33:17.000 --> 33:20.000
We look at the accounting maps of your company.

33:20.000 --> 33:22.000
That is, this must be taken into account.

33:22.000 --> 33:27.000
And we look at the marketing results of the external environment.

33:27.000 --> 33:31.000
These additional tools will help us analyze the situation as it is.

33:41.000 --> 33:51.000
Now, let's move on to the most important point.

33:51.000 --> 33:56.000
Now we will talk about the identification of business processes.

33:56.000 --> 34:00.000
So, where does it all start?

34:00.000 --> 34:04.000
We start with the allocation of business processes of the very highest level.

34:05.000 --> 34:11.000
In other words, we roughly divide the activities of your company into several main blocks.

34:11.000 --> 34:13.000
There will be about 20 of them.

34:13.000 --> 34:15.000
There will be 30, 40, 50.

34:15.000 --> 34:17.000
Cut it out.

34:17.000 --> 34:19.000
This means that you have highlighted too much detail.

34:19.000 --> 34:27.000
Second, we divide your organizational structure as it is now into departments, groups, units, etc.

34:27.000 --> 34:29.000
While we describe everything as it is.

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
That is, we describe the business processes at the top level as it is,

34:32.000 --> 34:35.000
the organizational structure as it is, and then the distribution of responsibilities as it is.

34:35.000 --> 34:37.000
This is all as it is.

34:37.000 --> 34:40.000
How are business processes of the top level identified?

34:40.000 --> 34:46.000
So, we are now recalling what your organization was created for.

34:46.000 --> 34:50.000
What are the main business directions of its activities?

34:50.000 --> 34:56.000
Based on these business directions, we can identify what are the main business processes of your business.

34:57.000 --> 35:04.000
For example, your company was created to develop marketing concepts of other companies.

35:04.000 --> 35:08.000
For example, you are a consulting agency for the development of marketing strategies.

35:08.000 --> 35:16.000
This means that you can have business directions for the development of marketing concepts for small companies, for large companies, and, for example, for medium-sized companies.

35:16.000 --> 35:18.000
Because, in principle, these are different things.

35:18.000 --> 35:25.000
Or, if you are a dairy factory, then you can have business directions for dairy and dairy products.

35:26.000 --> 35:33.000
If you are a clothing agency, then it can be business directions for leather and fur, for example.

35:33.000 --> 35:41.000
That is, when we identify business processes at the top level, we start with business directions of your activities.

35:41.000 --> 35:42.000
So, we have identified it.

35:42.000 --> 35:44.000
The most basic.

35:44.000 --> 35:51.000
I want to say right away that you do not need to confuse what is called business direction and business options.

35:52.000 --> 36:01.000
That is, you do not need to select business directions from the series of products for jackets, leather, fur, and, for example, boots.

36:01.000 --> 36:04.000
This means that you have selected business directions incorrectly.

36:04.000 --> 36:07.000
You should have a single criterion for selecting business directions.

36:07.000 --> 36:08.000
This is A.

36:08.000 --> 36:10.000
Either the material, that is, leather or fur.

36:10.000 --> 36:13.000
Or it will be the type of product, clothes or shoes.

36:13.000 --> 36:18.000
Or it will be according to the consumer, physical or legal.

36:18.000 --> 36:20.000
That is, you do not need to mix everything into one pile.

36:20.000 --> 36:23.000
You select business directions according to some criteria.

36:23.000 --> 36:30.000
Then you can further divide, for example, leather products into clothes, shoes, and so on.

36:30.000 --> 36:33.000
We have selected business directions for your activities.

36:33.000 --> 36:42.000
For example, you are a company that deals with the construction and technological support of these built objects.

36:42.000 --> 36:43.000
Well, for example.

36:44.000 --> 36:57.000
Let's say that we have now determined that your main business processes will be related to construction and technological support.

36:57.000 --> 37:00.000
All other business processes are our providers.

37:00.000 --> 37:03.000
They have nothing to do with the main business process.

37:03.000 --> 37:08.000
To what level do you need to describe business directions?

37:09.000 --> 37:11.000
In principle, it can be at this level.

